<subSubSection id="7BFD11465F9ECF11210FE0F0A17E4834" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" type="circumscription">
<paragraph id="CF5B1D6FA3391A983A5FAE05722A2B65" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Circumscription.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="84D92FD323A3121DEC450B55BEE2E566" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicName id="D56E609AD4C20D54BACD277E39B6A532" authority="subg. Monochoria" authorityName="subg. Monochoria (C. Presl) M. Pell. &amp; C. N. Horn" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="subg. Cabanisia (Klotzsch ex Schltdl.) M. Pell. &amp; C. N. Horn" baseAuthorityYear="2018" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Pontederia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="subg." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pontederia" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus" subGenus="Monochoria">Pontederia subg. Monochoria</taxonomicName>
is composed of ten exclusively Paleotropical species. All species occur in permanently moist environments or shallow waters, growing either as erect or procumbent-emergent, resembling in habit smaller members of 
<taxonomicName id="2B4D29D51F0B60745081284DD7AA04E4" authority="subg. Pontederia" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." infraspecific-rank="subg." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P." order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="genus" subGenus="Pontederia">P. subg. Pontederia</taxonomicName>
and even some species of 
<taxonomicName id="417AE7E7E5C43F7FBD38B419FAD1C478" class="Liliopsida" family="Haemodoraceae" genus="Heteranthera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Heteranthera" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3B6A326F93EB1DA4B3C9493D67CCE804" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Heteranthera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The members of this subgenus are quite unique within 
<taxonomicName id="433CA8A8A9768D39B3A313B855ACFFD1" authorityName="subg. Monochoria (C. Presl) M. Pell. &amp; C. N. Horn" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="subg. Cabanisia (Klotzsch ex Schltdl.) M. Pell. &amp; C. N. Horn" baseAuthorityYear="2018" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Pontederia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pontederia" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CAE9A13B718DC5203D7D67FD254EE22D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Pontederia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="8585B0A2AAD127C8E1321F4723A0CF6B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">s.l.</emphasis>
due to their pedicellate flowers, perianth only basally connate, unequal stamens, basifixed and poricidal anthers and due to the secondary loss of the septal nectaries.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9D048B395A4496835E633717923693A1" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="995930884B9F821007F337BE990C1329" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A42B8224AA4E88AD3F0A45E149F77779" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">
Exclusively Paleotropical (
<bibRefCitation id="920C7437EAA8BEA7A93659A26E2FAE97" author="Cook, CDK" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe botanique de France" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" refId="B20" refString="Cook, CDK, 1989. Taxonomic revision of Monochoria (Pontederiaceae). In: Tan K, et al. (Eds) The Davis &amp; Hedge Festschrift: Plant Taxonomy, Phytogeography, and Related Subjects. Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh, 149-184." title="Taxonomic revision of Monochoria (Pontederiaceae). In: Tan K, et al. (Eds) The Davis &amp; Hedge Festschrift: Plant Taxonomy, Phytogeography, and Related Subjects. Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh, 149 - 184." year="1989">Cook 1989</bibRefCitation>
), with two species native to Africa (
<bibRefCitation id="35650DE255A282AEEFC3F950F7091FD7" author="Verdcourt, B" journalOrPublisher="Kirkia" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" pagination="80 - 83" refId="B119" refString="Verdcourt, B, 1961. The genus Monochoria C.Presl (Pontederiaceae) in Africa. Kirkia 1: 80 - 83" title="The genus Monochoria C. Presl (Pontederiaceae) in Africa." volume="1" year="1961">Verdcourt 1961</bibRefCitation>
), four to Australia (two endemic, 
<bibRefCitation id="B860383EAA318110836F50339BC15A8C" author="Aston, HI" journalOrPublisher="Muelleria" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" pagination="51 - 57" refId="B5" refString="Aston, HI, 1985. Monochoria cyanea and M. australasica (Pontederiaceae) in Australia. Muelleria 6 (1): 51 - 57" title="Monochoria cyanea and M. australasica (Pontederiaceae) in Australia." volume="6" year="1985">Aston 1985</bibRefCitation>
) and six to Asia (
<bibRefCitation id="799B7E441ABA432EE96AE0DBC1DA2378" author="Wang, G-X" journalOrPublisher="Current Topics in Plant Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" pagination="39 - 52" refId="B123" refString="Wang, G-X, Wei, L, Xiao-Chun, W, Itoh, K, 2004. Taxonomy of the genus Monochoria (Pontederiaceae) in Asia. Current Topics in Plant Biology 5: 39 - 52" title="Taxonomy of the genus Monochoria (Pontederiaceae) in Asia." volume="5" year="2004">Wang et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
